<subsection xml:id="subsec-distance-and-displacement" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Distance and Displacement</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.10 Linear Motion
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Distinguish between distance and displacement in different situations and apply concepts to solve real-world problems.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define distance as the total length of the path travelled (scalar) and displacement as the straight-line distance from start to end with direction (vector). Understand that distance is always greater than or equal to displacement.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate distance by adding path segments. Calculate displacement using the Pythagorean theorem for right-angle paths or by subtracting positions for linear paths.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving distance and displacement such as navigation, sports events, and journey analysis. Explain when displacement is more useful than distance.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/distance-and-displacement.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/linear-motion/step-by-step-guide_distance-and-displacement.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Walking Two Different Paths</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Work in small groups (3<ndash/>4 students)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p>
                    Chalk or masking tape, measuring tape or ruler, notebooks and pens
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Take students outside or use a large indoor space (gymnasium, hallway). Help groups mark points A, B, and C accurately using measuring tape. Ensure students understand the right-angle path (east then north). Guide students to measure the diagonal distance from A to C. Help students recognise that displacement is the same for both students despite different paths. Use student observations as a bridge to formal definitions.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p><q>Which path is shorter?</q></p></li>
                        <li><p><q>Does the displacement change based on the path taken?</q></p></li>
                        <li><p><q>Can displacement ever be greater than distance? Why not?</q></p></li>
                        <li><p><q>When will distance and displacement be equal?</q></p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            Identify 2<ndash/>3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What you need</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Chalk or masking tape to mark paths on the ground.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A measuring tape or ruler to measure distances.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A notebook and pen to record measurements and observations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Mark three points on the ground:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Point A (Start)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Point B (10 m east of A)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Point C (10 m north of B)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                        
                        <image source="distance_displacement.jpg">
                            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            One student to walk:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        From A to B (10 m east)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Then from B to C (10 m north)
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Another student to go directly from A to C (diagonal path).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Record: 
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Total distance for the first student (A to B to C).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Total distance for the second student (A to C).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Displacement (straight line from A to C) for both students.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                       
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compare the distance and displacement for both paths taken by the students. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Can displacement ever be greater than distance? Why not?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    When will distance and displacement be equal?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>

    <exploration xml:id="exploration-journey-distance-displacement">
        <title>The School Journey: Distance vs. Displacement</title>
        
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Suppose you travel from home to school, but along the way you pass through the market. Do you think the total distance you travel is the same as your overall change in position?
            </p>
            <p>
                 Run the animation below and investigate your ideas by following <xref ref="inst-dist-disp-journey" text="custom">the guiding questions below</xref>.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <figure xml:id="fig-journey-distance-displacement">
            <caption>Interactive Animation: Traveling from Home to School</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-journey" platform="jsxgraph" width="95%" aspect="4:3" source="jsxgraph/distance-displacement.js">
                <slate xml:id="jxgbox-anim-dist-disp" surface="jsxboard" aspect="4:3"/>
                <instructions xml:id="inst-dist-disp-journey">
                    <p>
                        Click <c>Start Journey</c> and carefully observe both the motion of the car and the numerical values displayed. You may click <c>Restart</c> at any time to return the car to Home and begin the investigation again.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <alert>Tracking the Route:</alert> As the car travels from Home to the Market and then turns toward School, how does the <term>Distance Traveled</term> change? Why does it continue increasing even after the car changes direction?
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <alert>Comparing the Two Measures:</alert> When the car reaches School, compare the final values of <term>Distance Traveled</term> and <term>Displacement</term>. Which is greater? What does this tell you about how each quantity is measured?
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <alert>Understanding Displacement:</alert> The blue dotted line represents displacement. What does this line measure that the red path does not?
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <alert>The Shortcut Question:</alert> If you could travel directly from Home to School in a perfectly straight line, which value would represent that trip: distance, displacement, or both?
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <alert>Making a General Rule:</alert> Based on what you observed, can displacement ever be greater than distance? Explain your reasoning.
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>
    <insight>
        <p>
            <term>Distance</term> is the total length of the path travelled by an object, regardless of direction.
        </p>
        <p>
            Distance tells us how much ground has been covered.
        </p>
        <p>
            Distance depends on the path taken.
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Displacement</term> is the straight-line distance from the starting point to the ending point, along with the direction.
        </p>
        <p>
            Displacement tells us how far and in what direction an object is from its starting point.
        </p>
        <p>
            Displacement depends only on the initial and final positions.
        </p>
        <p>
            Distance is always greater than or equal to displacement.
        </p>
        <p>
            Real-life examples where displacement is more useful than distance:
            <ul>
                <li>Navigation systems like GPS: Displacement gives the straight-line distance and direction to the destination, which is more useful than the total distance traveled.</li>
                <li>Sports events: In events like long jump or javelin throw, displacement measures how far an athlete has moved from the starting point in a specific direction.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Formalizing Distance and Displacement</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Whole class
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> Distance and displacement are the same thing. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Distance depends on the actual path taken, while displacement depends only on start and end positions.</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> Displacement can be greater than distance. <alert>Clarification:</alert> The straight-line distance (displacement) can never exceed the total path length (distance).</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> Displacement is always positive. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Displacement is a vector and can be positive, negative, or zero depending on direction. It is zero when the object returns to its starting point.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Individual, then pairs for checking
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Walk through the first worked example on the board, then allow students to attempt the remaining examples independently. Circulate to check working and provide support where needed. Remind students to use the Pythagorean theorem for right-angle paths.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A person walks <m>3</m> m east, then <m>4</m> m north. What is the distance travelled and the displacement from the starting point?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Distance travelled} =\amp 3 \, \text{m} + 4 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 7 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Displacement can be found using the Pythagorean theorem: 
            </p>
            <p>
                
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Displacement} =\amp \sqrt{(3 \, \text{m})^2 + (4 \, \text{m})^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 5 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A learner walks <m>5</m> m east and then <m>3</m> m west. What is the distance travelled?
            </p>
            <p>
                What is the displacement from the starting point?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Distance travelled} =\amp 5 \, \text{m} + 3 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 8 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Displacement}=\amp \text{Final Position - Initial Position} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 5 \, \text{m} - 3 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 2 \, \text{m east}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                 A student jogs <m>100</m> meters east and then <m>100</m> meters west.
                  What are the total distance and displacement?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{ Distance} =\amp 100 \, \text{m} + 100 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 200 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Displacement} =\amp \text{Final Position - Initial Position} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 100 \, \text{m} - 100 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 0 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A person walks <m>3</m> m west, then <m>4</m> m south. 
                Find the total distance traveled and the displacement.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Distance} =\amp 3 \, \text{m} + 4 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 7 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Displacement} =\amp \sqrt{(3 \, \text{m})^2 + (4 \, \text{m})^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 5 \, \text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                The displacement is <m>5 \, \text{m}</m> in a south-west direction.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment <mdash/> Exit Ticket</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Individual
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Exit Ticket Questions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="1.">
                        <li>
                            <p>A delivery driver travels 12 km north from the warehouse, then 5 km east to make a delivery.</p>
                            <p>
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li><p>Calculate the total distance traveled.</p></li>
                                    <li><p>Calculate the displacement from the warehouse.</p></li>
                                    <li><p>Explain why the displacement is less than the distance.</p></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>A student walks 8 m forward along a straight corridor, then turns around and walks 3 m back.</p>
                            <p>
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li><p>What is the total distance walked?</p></li>
                                    <li><p>What is the displacement from the starting position?</p></li>
                                    <li><p>In what direction is the student displaced?</p></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="1.">
                        <li><p>(a) Distance <m>= 12 + 5 = 17</m> km. (b) Displacement <m>= \sqrt{12^2 + 5^2} = \sqrt{169} = 13</m> km. (c) Displacement is the straight-line distance from start to finish, while distance includes the actual path taken.</p></li>
                        <li><p>(a) Distance <m>= 8 + 3 = 11</m> m. (b) Displacement <m>= 8 - 3 = 5</m> m. (c) The student is displaced 5 m forward from the starting position.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-distance-and-displacement">
        <title>Exercise</title>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A car travels <m>60</m> km north and then <m>80</m> km east. What is the total distance travelled and the displacement from the starting point?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Distance travelled  <m>= 140 \, \text{km}</m>.
                </p>
                
                <p>
                    Displacement <m>= 100 \, \text{km}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A student walks <m>5</m> m east and then <m>3</m> m west. What is the distance travelled and the displacement from the starting point?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Distance travelled <m>= 8 \, \text{m}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Displacement <m>= 2 \, \text{m east}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A person walks <m>6</m> meters north, then <m>8</m> meters east. Calculate the distance and displacement.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Distance <m>= 14 \, \text{m}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Displacement <m>= 10 \, \text{m}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A student runs around a rectangular park of length <m>60 \, \text{m}</m> and width <m>40 \, \text{m}</m> and returns to the starting point. 
                    Find the distance and displacement.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Distance <m>= 2(60 \, \text{m} + 40 \, \text{m}) = 200 \, \text{m}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Displacement <m>= 0 \, \text{m}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Can the displacement of an object be greater than its distance? Explain why or why not.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    No, the displacement of an object cannot be greater than its distance. 
                    This is because distance is the total length of the path traveled, while displacement is the straight-line distance from the starting point to the ending point.
                    The straight-line distance (displacement) can never exceed the total path length (distance).
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
        
        
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Use grid paper to draw paths and visualise distance vs. displacement.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide pre-drawn diagrams with labelled paths.</p></li>
                <li><p>Start with simple one-dimensional motion (east<ndash/>west only).</p></li>
                <li><p>Use physical demonstrations with students walking paths.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide Pythagorean theorem reference for right-angle calculations.</p></li>
                <li><p>Allow calculators for all calculations.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Encourage students to explain the difference between distance and displacement in their own words.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide mixed practice with both linear and right-angle paths.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask students to identify when distance equals displacement.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Introduce three-dimensional displacement problems.</p></li>
                <li><p>Explore vector notation for displacement.</p></li>
                <li><p>Challenge with complex multi-leg journeys.</p></li>
                <li><p>Investigate displacement in circular motion.</p></li>
                <li><p>Analyse real GPS data showing distance vs. displacement.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity <mdash/> School Navigation Project:</alert> Choose two locations in or around the school. Identify at least three different walking routes between them. Measure and record the distance for each route. Calculate the displacement (straight-line distance) between the two locations. Create a map showing all routes with distances labelled. Compare the efficiency of each route (distance vs. displacement). Present findings to the class explaining which route is most efficient and why.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
</subsection>